.TH EUCLID "1" "February 2026" "Jacob Niemeir" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
Euclid \- A x86_64 Linux application sandboxing utility, created for educational purposes.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B euclid

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B euclid
creates an isolated execution environment using Linux namespaces, cgroups v2, and seccomp-bpf filtering. 
It launches a sandboxed process with restricted system access and resource limits.

Provides: 
.IP \(bu 2
UTS, PID, mount, network, and IPC namespace isolation
.IP \(bu 2
Resource limits via cgroups v2 (CPU, memory, swap, PIDs)
.IP \(bu 2
Syscall filtering via seccomp-bpf
.IP \(bu 2
Filesystem isolation with pivot_root
.IP \(bu 2
Capability dropping

.SH CONFIGURATION
All configuration is compile-time and must be set in 
.I src/context.c
before building.

.TP
.B HOSTNAME
Container hostname (default: "euclid")

.TP
.B ROOTFS
Path to root filesystem (default: "/home/noodle/alpine")

.TP
.B CMD
Command to execute in container (default: "/bin/sh")

.TP
.B CPU_MAX
CPU quota in cgroups format (default: "100000, 100000")

.TP
.B MEM_MAX
Hard memory limit in bytes (default: 512000000)

.TP
.B PIDS_MAX
Maximum number of processes (default: 256)

